    "deviation_details": "n=0.00001 gives L3=113 (vs 116). Confirmed at both 500 and 2000 samples. SVD analysis shows sv(114-116) drop to ~1e-11 (noise floor) while sv(113) is ~4e-7. This is a numerical resolution limit as the potential approaches constant (u^0 = 1). The sharp transition from 116→113 occurs between n=0.0001 (clear gap at 116) and n=0.00001 (gap at 113). This suggests the algebraic structure is genuinely 116-dimensional for all n>0 but the functional independence of three generators degrades exponentially as n→0.",
    "conclusion": "Potential universality extends continuously to non-integer exponents across the full range [0.0001, 3.5]. The dimension sequence [3, 6, 17, 116] is invariant to the choice of exponent — not just for integer values, but for arbitrary real exponents including 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, and values infinitesimally close to integers (e.g., 0.99999, 1.00001, 1.99999, 2.00001). The only apparent deviation at n=0.00001 is an SVD resolution artifact as the potential approaches constant."
